{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585501"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:13:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:13:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14984"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115433"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7672"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97436"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"7649"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115433"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAntibodies are composed of heavy and light chain proteins that are encoded by genes located on different chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the chromosomal locations of antibody genes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heavy chain on chromosome 14, kappa on chromosome 2, lambda on chromosome 22","Heavy chain on chromosome 2, kappa on chromosome 14, lambda on chromosome 22","Heavy chain on chromosome 22, kappa on chromosome 2, lambda on chromosome 14","Heavy chain on chromosome 14, kappa on chromosome 22, lambda on chromosome 2","Heavy chain on chromosome 2, kappa on chromosome 22, lambda on chromosome 14"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct chromosomal locations for antibody genes are: \u003Cstrong\u003Eheavy chain on chromosome 14, kappa light chain on chromosome 2, and lambda light chain on chromosome 22\u003C/strong\u003E. This arrangement allows for independent genetic recombination events that contribute to antibody diversity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options present various mismatched combinations of these chromosomal locations. \u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy chain on chromosome 2, kappa on chromosome 14, lambda on chromosome 22\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly places the heavy chain gene. \u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy chain on chromosome 22, kappa on chromosome 2, lambda on chromosome 14\u003C/strong\u003E misplaces both heavy chain and lambda genes. \u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy chain on chromosome 14, kappa on chromosome 22, lambda on chromosome 2\u003C/strong\u003E switches the locations of kappa and lambda genes. \u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy chain on chromosome 2, kappa on chromosome 22, lambda on chromosome 14\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly places all three genes. These distinct chromosomal locations are fundamental to understanding genetic recombination in antibody production and the generation of antibody diversity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The heavy chain gene of antibodies is located on chromosome 14.","The light chain kappa gene is located on chromosome 2.","The light chain lambda gene is located on chromosome 22.","These distinct chromosomal locations allow for independent genetic recombination to generate antibody diversity."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Chapter 9, The Humoral Immune Response. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10752/","Class switching is a crucial process in the immune system that allows B cells to produce different classes of antibodies, each with distinct functions. This process is essential for the adaptive immune response, enabling the body to effectively respond to various pathogens."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97436"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97436"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:36:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:36:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7672"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115433"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na